@node Over "Overview"

MCE (Multi-game Character Editor) allows editing of character files, saved
games and high score tables for these 60 games:

    * Bard's Tale 1-3 & Construction Set (1987-1992)     S
    * BattleTech (1989)                                  S
    * Bloodwych (1989)                                   S
    * Chambers of Shaolin (1989)                         S
    * Champions of Krynn (1990)                          S
    * Citadel of Vras (1989)                             S
    * Dark Castle (1988)                                 H
    * Deja Vu 1 & 2 (1986-1989)                          S
    * Demon's Winter (1989)                              S
    * Dragon Wars (1990)                                 S
    * Druid 2 (1988)                                     H
    * Eye of the Beholder 1 & 2 (1990-1992)              S
    * Faery Tale Adventure (1986)                        S
    * Grand Monster Slam (1989)                          H
    * Great Giana Sisters/Hard 'n' Heavy (1988-1989)     H
    * GridStart 1-3 (1987-1988)                          H
    * Heroes of the Lance (1988)                         S
    * Hillsfar (1989)                                    S
    * Impossible Mission 2 (1988)                       H+S
    * Keef the Thief (1989)                              S
    * Legend of Faerghail (1990)                         S
    * Legend of Lothian (1991)                           S
    * Might & Magic 2 (1990)                             S
    * Neuromancer (1989)                                 S
    * Nitro (1990)                                       H
    * Phantasie 1 & 3 (1987)                             S
    * Pinball Dreams/Fantasies/Illusions (1992-1995)     H
    * Pirates! (1990)                                    S
    * Pool of Radiance (1990)                            S
    * Questron 2 (1988)                                  S
    * Return of the Jedi (1988)                          H
    * Rockford (1988)                                    H
    * Rogue (1986)                                      H+S
    * Shadowgate (1987)                                  S
    * Shadowlands (1992)                                 S
    * Sinbad and the Throne of the Falcon (1987)         S
    * Temple of Apshai (1986)                            S
    * Times of Lore (1988)                               S
    * Transylvania 1 & 2 (1986)                          S
    * Ultima 3-6 (1986-1992)                             S
    * Uninvited (1987)                                   S
    * Winter Games (1987)                                H
    * Wizardry 6 (1990)                                  S
    * World Games (1987)                                 H
    * Zerg (1989)                                        S

H = High score tables
S = Saved games/characters

@{b}General notes and warnings@{ub}

It is suggested that you make a backup of (the unedited versions of) your
files before using the editor.
  If you want to save the changes you have made, you must do so explicitly
(eg. via the toolbar or menu).
  It is not necessarily safe to set certain attributes to the maximum
allowed by the editor, as not every attribute has been exhaustively tested
for its allowable range. Also, the editor will allow you to set eg. your
current hit points to be higher than your maximum hit points, but doing
this is not recommended.
  Different game versions might use different file formats which may not
be compatible with the editor. Generally, where a WHDLoad slave is
available for a game, the editor is intended for use with that slave and
might not be intended for use with the floppy version.
  Files which you have previously hacked by hand might not be safe to load
into the game and/or editor.
  High score tables are automatically sorted for you before they are
saved.
  There are example vanilla saves for all games (except Grand Monster
Slam) provided in the Examples/ directory, so that you can easily browse
the capabilities of the program.
@endnode

@node Requ "System Requirements"

@{b}Hardware@{ub}         Required        MC68020+
                                 about 2Mb free RAM
                 Recommended     1024*768 or higher Workbench
@{b}Firmware@{ub}         Required        Kickstart 3.1+
@{b}Software@{ub}         Required        AmigaOS 3.9 with Boing Bag 1 (at least)
                 Recommended     OpenURL.library (if OS < 4.1.1)
                                 TCP/IP stack

This program does not operate under the "AmigaOS 3.x" provided by Cloanto
in eg. the Amiga Forever 6.0 package, as it requires OS3.9+BB1 (or later)
versions of certain ReAction gadgets. The versions included in "AmigaOS
3.x" are obsolete and will not work. We suggest asking Cloanto for the
real OS3.9 which you have paid them for and which they have not supplied
to you, rather than a crippled version of OS3.5 which is basically what
their "AmigaOS 3.x" is.

If you have the Amiga Image Storage System (AISS) installed, you can
delete the images/aiss/ subdirectory.

For MorphOS users:

You need the appropriate ClassAct/ReAction classes (eg. window.class,
speedbar.gadget, etc.) installed. You can get these classes at
http://amigan.1emu.net/releases/RA-MOS.lha . Those files are sourced from
AmigaOS 3.9+BB2, except that window.class V42.84 is provided instead of
V45.16. This is because MorphOS is incompatible with window.class 45.16:
opening it will cause a hang. Simply copy these ReAction classes into
SYS:Classes/ . Although they are compiled for 68020, they will work under
MorphOS.
@endnode

@node Usag "Usage"

@{b}CLI Arguments@{ub}

                                    @{b}MCE@{ub}

@{b}Format:    MCE@{ub} [PUBSCREEN <pubscreen>] [[FUNCTION] <function>]
           [FILE <file>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}  PUBSCREEN/K,FUNCTION/N

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}   To edit saved games for various games.

@{b}Specification:@{ub}

    pubscreen=<pubscreen>:
           the name of a public screen to open on (otherwise the default
           public screen is used).

    function=<number>:
           the ordinal number of the function you wish to jump to. These
           correspond as follows:

            1    Bard's Tale series
            2    BattleTech
            3    Bloodwych
            4    Chambers of Shaolin
            5    Champions of Krynn
            6    Citadel of Vras
            7    Dark Castle
            8    Deja Vu 1 & 2
            9    Demon's Winter
           10    Dragon Wars
           11    Druid 2
           12    Eye of the Beholder 1 & 2
           13    Faery Tale Adventure
           14    Grand Monster Slam
           15    Great Giana Sisters/Hard 'n' Heavy
           16    GridStart 1-3
           17    Heroes of the Lance
           18    Hillsfar
           19    Impossible Mission 2
           20    Keef the Thief
           21    Legend of Faerghail
           22    Legend of Lothian
           23    Might & Magic 2
           24    Neuromancer
           25    Nitro
           26    Phantasie 1 & 3
           27    Pinball Dreams/Fantasies/Illusions
           28    Pirates!
           29    Pool of Radiance
           30    Questron 2
           31    Return of the Jedi
           32    Rockford
           33    Rogue
           34    Shadowgate
           35    Shadowlands
           36    Sinbad and the Throne of the Falcon
           37    Temple of Apshai
           38    Times of Lore
           39    Transylvania 1 & 2
           40    Ultima 3
           41    Ultima 4
           42    Ultima 5
           43    Ultima 6
           44    Uninvited
           45    Winter Games
           46    Wizardry 6
           47    World Games
           48    Zerg

@{b}Workbench Tool Types@{ub}

These are not usable if MCE is compiled with StormC.

PUBSCREEN=<pubscreen>
FUNCTION=<function>

These are equivalent to the relevant CLI arguments.
@endnode

@node BTCE "Bard's Tale 1-3 & Construction Set"

The program autodetects the type of file being opened.
  The program allows considerable freedom to make alterations to the
characters; thus, discretion is advised. Don't forget to save your
character before quitting the program if you want to keep the changes
you have made.
  The checkboxes indicate whether the relevant item is "equipped" or not.
Next to each checkbox is an integer gadget which stores the quantity of
that item. 255 is a magic number meaning "unlimited". The ellipses (...)
when clicked will bring up a subwindow allowing you to change which item
is stored in that slot. If a particular item is not available in that
game, it will be shown in white.
  Values which can't be displayed by the game, eg. ST of 100 or more, are
shown in the game as asterisks (eg. "**"), "WOW", or similar. They still
work normally even if displayed in this manner.

BT2 Notes:

Images are used only for monsters/illusions.
Items can be carried by anyone.

BT3 Notes:

Images are used for everyone.
Items can be carried only by players.
The THIEVES.INF file is what is edited.

BTCS Notes:

Images are not used for anyone.
Items can be carried by anyone.
The ROSTER.CHR file is what is edited.
The sample scenario (Starlight Festival) is assumed, as far as items are
concerned.
@endnode

@node Bloodwych "Bloodwych"

Low armour classes are better than high ones.
  This editor has only been designed for and tested with the original
Bloodwych; it may or may not work with the expansion(s). Please advise us
of your results.
@endnode

@node ChambersOfShaolin "Chambers of Shaolin"

This editor is designed for the WHDLoad version (V1.1 was tested). The
floppy version seems to use a different format.
  There is a confirmed bug in that slave, in that only the first character
"slot" can be used. Therefore, this editor only supports editing the first
character slot. Hopefully, that bug will be fixed soon.
  The "hidden" attributes are not displayed in-game. However, if these are
too low, some moves (eg. jump kick) may not be available. This applies at
least to the hidden #2-#4 values; the purpose of the hidden #1 value has
not yet been ascertained.
@endnode

@node ChampionsOfKrynn "Champions Of Krynn"

Note that viewing/editing of items is not currently supported.
  Also note that characters are what is edited (not saved games).
@endnode

@node COVCE "Citadel of Vras"

The game detects attempts to alter certain fields and will quit in such
situations. Therefore those fields are read-only in the editor, for now at
least. You can freely teleport around, change your inventory, etc. Eg. you
can give yourself expensive items and then teleport to the shop
(coordinates 6,3,1) to sell them.

There is a HD-installed version of this game, and maps of it, at
http://amigan.1emu.net/aw/ .
@endnode

@node DejaVu "Deja Vu 1 & 2"

Not all props/items are actually openable in-game.
@endnode

@node DWCE "Demon's Winter"

The program allows considerable freedom to make alterations to the
characters; thus, discretion is advised. Don't forget to save your
character before quitting the program if you want to keep the changes
you have made.
  The checkboxes indicate whether the relevant item is "equipped" or not.
Next to each checkbox is an integer gadget which stores the quantity of
that item. 255 is a magic number meaning "unlimited". The ellipses (...)
when clicked will bring up a subwindow allowing you to change which item
is stored in that slot.
@endnode

@node FTACE "Faery Tale Adventure"

Turning on the trainer allows these cheats during the game:

    ARROW KEYS____Move very fast over any terrain.
    'B'__________________________Summon gold swan.
    'R'___________________________Rescue princess.
    '='_______________________Display coordinates.
    'F9'________________Increase time by one hour.
    'F10'_________________Location in coordinates.
@endnode

@node DragonWars "Dragon Wars"

Blank (empty) character and item names seem to indicate to the game that
the character or item in question does not exist (ie. that the slot is
unused). Editing nonexistent characters/items to "create" new characters/
items is untested and might be problematic.
  The checkboxes next to the item names are for whether the item is
"equipped" or not.
  Editing item names does not change the actual characteristics of the
items.
  "Min" indicates the minimum strength/dexterity/etc. required to use the
item.
@endnode

@node HCE "Hillsfar"

Since the Curse of the Azure Bonds game supports importing (and exporting)
characters from (and to) Hillsfar, it can also be useful for that game.
  The program allows considerable freedom to make alterations to the
characters; thus, discretion is advised. Don't forget to save your
character before quitting the program if you want to keep the changes you
have made.
  Usage is reasonably straightforward. You must supply an existing
character file (#?.HIL) from Hillsfar for editing (an example file is
provided). Note that you should use a filename which is no more than 8
characters, not including the ".HIL" extension, otherwise the game will
not be able to load the character. (The convention used by the game is to
use the first 8 characters of the character name, but this is not
strictly required.)
  When playing Hillsfar, you can press 'F' to force locks. Also, there is
a map available from the site.
@endnode

@node ImpossibleMission2 "Impossible Mission 2"

You can edit saved games (normally named "game") or high score tables
(normally named "score"). MCE will detect the file type and configure
itself accordingly.
@endnode

@node KeefTheThief "Keef the Thief"

Note that there is a known issue with the WHDLoad slave (V1.0): after
viewing the inventory (eg. via the "Keef|Inventory" command), the game
will crash with an access fault. This is not a bug in MCE and occurs
independently of it. The solution is to add the EXPCHIP ToolType to the
slave icon.
@endnode

@node LegendOfFaerghail "Legend of Faerghail"

The supported version of the game is V2.0e.
  Do not leave any empty item slots between your items.
  The checkboxes indicate whether the relevant item is "equipped" or not.
  The character roster is what is edited (not saved games).
@endnode

@node Might&Magic2 "Might & Magic 2"

Characters 1-24 are normal characters; characters 25-48 are hirelings.
  Note that the contents of the Spellbook list are dependent on the
character's class. This is by design. (Clerics and sorcerers have separate
spell lists, and other classes have no spells.)
@endnode

@node NCE "Neuromancer"

Ticked body parts indicate an original (good) body part. Unticked body
parts indicate a replacement (bad) body part.
@endnode

@node PCE "Phantasie 1 & 3"

The program allows considerable freedom to make alterations to the
characters; thus, discretion is advised. Don't forget to save your
character before quitting the program if you want to keep the changes
you have made.
  The ellipses (...) when clicked will bring up a subwindow allowing you
to change which item is stored in that slot. Unavailable choices are shown
in white.
  Usage is reasonably straightforward. You must supply an existing
character roster file from either Phantasie 1 (GUILD.DAT) or Phantasie 3
(GAMESAVE.DAT) for editing. It is unfortunately not possible to convert
characters between the two games using this editor (although note that it
is possible to use the Phantasie 3 game to convert (transfer) characters
from Phantasie 1 to Phantasie 3).

Phantasie 1 notes:
  It is unfortunately not possible to edit potions, scrolls or treasures.
  The 'purged' flag is set by the game when a character is deleted; ie. it
is possible to 'undelete' a character by unchecking the checkbox.

Phantasie 3 notes:
  Character slots #1-#25 are the main roster of guild members. Character
slots #26-#32 are the seven party members. It is best to drop characters
from the party first (Guild|Drop Member in the game) before editing them,
as the game seems to use some stats from the roster slot and some stats
from the party slot.
  No character may know more than 32 spells; this is a limit imposed by
the file format itself.
  Unfortunately the 'purged' flag is not editable (or viewable, for that
matter). Therefore, you should not try to create new characters with the
editor; you should instead create them within the game and then use the
editor.
@endnode

@node Pinball "Pinball Dreams/Fantasies/Illusions"

This is designed for the AGA versions (except Pinball Dreams); it has not
been tested with the OCS or CDł˛ versions.
@endnode

@node Pirates "Pirates!"

Currently, only Pirates! is supported, not Pirates! Gold.
  Making changes to your cargo (food, etc.) or ships should be done with
caution, as it can cause encumbrance-related issues.
  These abbreviations are used in the cities subwindow:

   F: Forts    (in ones)
   S: Soldiers (in tens)
   C: Citizens (in hundreds)
   $: Gold     (in thousands)

For MorphOS users:
  There is an incompatibility between texteditor.gadget (eg. V15.8) and
MorphOS. Therefore, editing the description field is not permitted when
running under MorphOS.
@endnode

@node PoolOfRadiance "Pool of Radiance"

It is easy to cause overflow of in-game amounts (eg. damage inflicted),
so be conservative with your editing.
  Editing of your portrait and of your "icon" is MCE is unnecessary and
therefore not implemented. (You can freely edit these in-game while
encamped.)
  Note that viewing/editing of items is not currently supported.
  Also note that characters are what is edited (not saved games).
@endnode

@node Q2CE "Questron 2"

The program allows considerable freedom to make alterations to the
characters; thus, discretion is advised. Carrying all/nearly all weapons +
armour + items can cause rendering problems in the game. Don't forget to
save your character before quitting the program if you want to keep the
changes you have made.
  Usage is reasonably straightforward. You must supply an existing
character file (G0-G7) from Questron 2 for editing. The NAMES file is also
updated appropriately when saving, if it can be found in the same
directory as the character file (G0-G7), which is normally the case.
@endnode

@node Rogue "Rogue"

This is intended for the Epyx release of the game (as opposed to eg.
http://aminet.net/game/role/Rogue11.lha). V1.48 of the game was tested
(the version number is shown by pressing the 'V' key during play).
  You can edit saved games or hall of fame (high score table) files. MCE
will detect the file type and configure itself accordingly.
@endnode

@node Shadowgate "Shadowgate"

This editor is intended to be used with V1.0 of the WHDLoad slave.
There seem to be problems with this slave (at least on this computer):
the game can randomly crash back to Workbench, eg. when booting,
when accessing menus, when loading saved games. This doesn't mean the
saved game is corrupt, so try again.
  Not all props/items are actually openable in-game.
@endnode

@node Shadowlands "Shadowlands"

This editor is intended to be used with (V1.6 of) the WHDLoad slave.
  Viewing/editing of items, faces, etc. is not currently supported.
  Be aware that loading a game in the WHDLoad version takes about 30
seconds, for some reason.
@endnode

@node Sinbad "Sinbad and the Throne of the Falcon"

The various NPCs can move around and therefore will not necessarily stay
for long where you put them.
  Obviously it is not wise to move the Sabaralus (your ship) inland.
  The WHDLoad slave V1.2 seems to have bugs: your ship can randomly
permanently disappear. Additionally, when talking to characters, their
final answer is displayed only very briefly. We suggest using the floppy
version of the game.
@endnode

@node TempleOfApshai "Temple of Apshai"

All 3 "games" in the Temple of Apshai Trilogy are supported.
  You can edit character files (as stored in the Characters/ directory)
or saved game files (eg. dngns/cip). MCE will detect the file
type and configure itself accordingly.
  Although room numbers can range up to 60, most dungeons have less rooms
than this. Changing to a nonexistent room will cause problems.
@endnode

@node TOLCE "Times of Lore"

The program allows considerable freedom to make alterations to the
characters; thus, discretion is advised. Don't forget to save your
character before quitting the program if you want to keep the changes you
have made. The game imposes a limit of 12 items that can be carried
simultaneously.
  Note that the sphere has no in-game imagery until you actually examine
it, and the Scroll of Life has no in-game imagery.
@endnode

@node UCE "Ultima 3-6"

Ultima 3:

"Maximize party" maximizes all characters.

ROST.BIN is the data for the 20 characters who are in the roster.
PLRS.BIN is the data for the 4 characters who are in the party.
In the game:
  "Form the party" writes 4 characters from ROST.BIN to PLRS.BIN.
  "Disperse the party" writes 4 characters from PLRS.BIN to ROST.BIN.

Ultima 4:

For more information about the file format, see
http://xu4.svn.sourceforge.net/viewvc/xu4/trunk/u4/doc/AmigaFileFormats.txt
  Only the ROST.BIN file is currently supported for editing. The PRTY.BIN
contains certain saved game data but is not currently viewable/editable.

Ultima 4-5:

You cannot change the number of characters in the party, but you can edit
edit "unused" characters (ie. characters who have not yet joined the
party).
  "Maximize character" maximizes attributes which are specific to that
character. "Maximize party" maximizes other attributes (ie. those which
are general to the entire party).

Ultima 5:

It might be necessary to "unready" your equipment before using the editor.
  It is not recommended to change location from one dungeon to another,
nor from one dungeon level to another, as the old map data may still be
used.
  Note that MCE shows dates in DD/MM/YYY format, whereas the game shows
them in MM-DD-YYY format.
  Most locations don't allow the full range of floors and X/Y-coordinates.
Eg. only Britannia/Underworld supports high X/Y-coordinates. Use of
improper combinations may cause the game to crash.
  To see the end sequence:

    * Maximize the party.
    * Set location to Doom, X: 4, Y: 7, dungeon level 7.
    * Go east.
    * All characters walk through the mirror.

Ultima 6:

(The WHDLoad slave V1.0 of) V1.12 of the game was tested. Other versions
are untested and might not work correctly.
  The condition (poisoned, asleep, etc.) of your characters is
automatically fixed by the editor when saving, but is not shown.
  Note that viewing/editing of items is not currently supported.
@endnode

@node Wizardry6 "Wizardry 6"

You must have at least one character in the party to be able to load the
saved game (ie. if you save at the game's title screen before adding any
characters, you can't edit that file yet).
@endnode

@node ZCE "Zerg"

Obviously, you should copy your saved game to somewhere other than RAM: if
you want to keep it permanently.
  You can get this game from http://aminet.net/game/role/Zerg.lha or from
Fish Disk #252 (http://aminet.net/misc/fish/fish-0252.lha).
@endnode

